(8, 'document', 'text/html', 'JFK University', '', '', 'jfk-university', '', 1, 0, 0, 3, 0, 'JFK University is a private, non-profit educational institution based in Pleasant Hill, California.', '<h4>Mission</h4>\r\n<p>“Our mission is to provide access to high-quality, innovative undergraduate, graduate, and doctoral educational opportunities that integrate theory and life experience we inspire personal, professional and academic growth and advance the well-being of our diverse local and global communities this mission is built upon our core values of accessibility, quality and innovation, transformative growth, diversity and global world view”</p>\r\n<h4>History</h4>\r\n<p>John F. Kennedy University was founded in 1964 and opened with 50 students with the mission of providing learning opportunities to adult learners who “despite a full range of life responsibilities, are determined to earn the benefits of advanced education to improve their future”.</p>\r\n<p>In 1977 the Graduate School of Holistic Studies was founded to “prepare students to work professionally for positive change in the world, based on their own direct experiences of personal growth and transformation.” By 1998 27% of the student body were enrolled in the Graduate School of Holistic Studies.</p>\r\n<p>Since the incorporation of JFKU into the National University System, the programs offered under the School of Holistic Studies have been subsumed into the College of Graduate and Professional Studies, along with courses in Management, Sports Psychology and Arts &amp; Consciousness.</p>\r\n<h4>Programming</h4>\r\n<p>The College of Graduate and Professional Studies at JFK University is comprised of several areas of study including:</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h5>Consciousness and Transformative Studies</h5>\r\n<p>“Consciousness &amp; Transformative Studies offers a multifaceted approach to the exploration of consciousness, particularly in relation to vocation, mentorship, sustainability and new paradigm thinking. This holistic curriculum integrates five major fields of study—psychology, philosophy, spirituality, deep ecology, sustainability and new science.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h5>Counseling Psychology and Counseling Psychology - Holistic</h5>\r\n<p>“The Master of Arts in Counseling Psychology – Holistic degree program builds on the foundation of counseling theory and practice to add a holistic perspective that integrates body, mind, spirit, and culture into the curriculum. The curriculum for this degree meets the educational requirements for the California Marriage and Family Therapist (MFT) License.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h5>Holistic Health Education</h5>\r\n<p>“The Holistic Health Education program reflects a cutting-edge understanding of theory and practice in health education from a holistic perspective, integrating body, mind, spirit, and community with a focus on promoting wellness. The Holistic Health Education program strives to develop a cadre of health educators who promote and embody a holistic vision of health both professionally and personally, acting from the highest values.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h5>Integral Studies</h5>\r\n<p>“The programs that comprise Integral Studies at John F. Kennedy University are designed to prepare individuals as agents of change in their communities by integrating inner truth and external realities. Students are taught to examine issues of today’s complex world by drawing upon and combining diverse perspectives to obtain a true understanding of their nature and to be able develop effective approaches and responses.”</p>\r\n<h4>Tuition</h4>\r\n<p>Masters programs typically require a student to complete between 50-70 units during their studies, costing $615/unit.</p>\r\n<p>MA: $33K-$43K</p>\r\n<p>Various Certificate Programs are available in most programs and cost from between $10K-$16K.</p>\r\n<h4>Contact</h4>\r\n<p>Ms. Paula Szloboda, MA, MBA</p>\r\n<p>Program Chair: Master of Arts in Holistic Health Education</p>\r\n<p>College of Graduate and Professional Studies</p>\r\n<p><a href="mailto:pszloboda@jfku.edu">pszloboda@jfku.edu</a></p>\r\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\r\n<p>Despite the inclusion of JFKU into the National University System and the inclusion of the holistic and integral studies programs into the broader stream of Graduate Professional Studies, the programs appear to be alive and well, still garnering respect from students and accreditation boards alike. However, it must be noted that the Chancellor of the National University System is now effectively has the last word in decisions regarding JFKU operations. His compensation is also closely tied (54% in 2010) to revenue growth of the overall program. Whether this represents a potential compromise of principals for the Holistic Studies program is unclear at this point.</p>\r\n<p>It should also be noted that JFKU appears to have unusually high overhead costs (37%) when compared to similar institutions (15%). The same is true of their compensation/total expenses ratio which was 67% in 2009, compared to an average of 35% at other educational institutions.</p>\r\n<p>The acceptance rate for the Holistic Studies program is also high: 85%. As is the overall acceptance rate: 65%.   </p>\r\n<p>Further questions need to be asked regarding how the affiliation with NUS has affected their overall mission effectiveness and what influence NUS has over programming and partnerships.</p>', 1, 11, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1365098670, 1, 1384878519, 0, 0, 0, 1365098640, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, 'research-categories/learning/jfk-university.html', 0, 0, 1, NULL),
(9, 'document', 'text/html', 'Naropa University', 'Naropa University', '', 'naropa', '', 1, 0, 0, 3, 0, 'Naropa is a contemplative education focused university in Boulder, CO', '<h2>Mission</h2>\r\n<p>“Accredited by The Higher Learning Commission and a member of the North Central Association, Naropa University is a private, nonprofit, nonsectarian liberal arts institution whose mission is contemplative education. This learning approach integrates the best of Eastern and Western educational traditions, enabling students to integrate academic knowledge with self-knowledge through contemplative practice.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h2> </h2>\r\n<h2>History</h2>\r\n<p><strong>1974</strong> - Founded as a Shambhala center for meditation and mindfullness</p>\r\n<p><strong>1975</strong> - First Degree programs in psychology and fine arts</p>\r\n<p><strong>1976</strong> - Naropa seeks accreditation from the North Central Association of Colleges and schools</p>\r\n<p><strong>1988</strong> - Naropa is recognized as one of only a handful of accredited Buddhist inspired universities in the country</p>\r\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Note: </strong>Naropa has formally disassociated itself from the Shambhala community, though it maintains its Buddhist centric philosophies and denotes Sakyong Mipham as its current lineage holder.</p>\r\n<h2> </h2>\r\n<h2> </h2>\r\n<h2>PROGRAM HIGHLIGHTS: UNDERGRADUATE</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Contemplative Psychology</strong></p>\r\n<p>Psychological studies, rooted in mindfulness</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Environmental Studies</strong></p>\r\n<p>Includes studies of rites of passage</p>\r\n<p>Interdisciplinary Studies</p>\r\n<p>Naropa students construct their own courses of study</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Peace Studies</strong></p>\r\n<p>Examining conflict and peacemaking</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Traditional Eastern Arts</strong></p>\r\n<p>Courses in TAi Chi and Yoga</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Writing and Literature</strong></p>\r\n<p>Creative Writing in Verse and Prose, taught by active writers</p>\r\n<h2> </h2>\r\n<h2>PROGRAM HIGHLIGHTS: GRADUATE</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Psychology Contemplative Psychotherapy</strong></p>\r\n<p>The only graduate program in the United States that joins psychotherapy training with Buddhist meditation</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Environmental Leadership</strong></p>\r\n<p>The only graduate program in the United States that joins psychotherapy training with Buddhist meditation</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Religious Studies</strong></p>\r\n<p>A two year program of study in Buddhism</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Transpersonal Counseling Psychology</strong></p>\r\n<p>Including Art Therapy</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Somatic Counseling Psychology </strong></p>\r\n<p>Movement thearapy eligible for Licensed Professional Counselor Examination</p>\r\n<h2> </h2>\r\n<h1> </h1>\r\n<h2>COLLABORATION WITH THE ROYAL UNIVERSITY OF BHUTAN</h2>\r\n<p>When establishing Naropa in the late 1960’s, the founder, Trungpa Rinpoche held a vision to bring Buddhism to America. For more than a decade, Bhutanese monks had been studying in the Naropa Religious Studies program. Then in the fall of 2008, collaboration began between Naropa and the Royal University of Bhutan (RUB) commenced to design a psychotherapy program and a teacher training program in mindfulness-awareness practice. The RUB itself already serves as the umbrella university of Bhutanese public higher education. </p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The curriculum design includes mindfulness, meditation, and a contemplative Bhuddist approach.  One unique aspect is a weeklong meditation retreat for teachers built into the program as an innovation for the Bhutanese.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Honorable Vice Chancelllor of the RUB, Dasho Pema Thinley and Naropa Contemplative Psychotherapy associate professor MacAndrew Jack along with Contemplative Psychology professor Jane Carpenter spent their sabbaticals to develop wisdom and methods of the Buddhist tradition into training of school counselors and to develop a master’s program in contemplative psychotherapy based on the Naropa University model.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Collaboration with Bhutanese lecturers had been done to bring contemplative psychotherapy into the design of a Postgraduate Diploma in School Counseling (PGDSC), which was the first-ever counseling program to be officered within the country.</p>', 1, 11, 2, 1, 1, 1, 1365098694, 30, 1372444492, 0, 0, 0, 1365098640, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, 'research-categories/learning/naropa.html', 0, 0, 1, NULL),
(11, 'document', 'text/html', 'Ackerman Institute', '', '', 'ackerman', '', 1, 0, 0, 6, 0, 'The Ackerman Institute for the Family is located on the Upper East Side of Manhattan', '<h4>Mission</h4>\r\n<p>“Founded in 1960, the Ackerman Institute for the Family is one of the premier institutions for family therapy in the United States. The Ackerman Institute provides state of the art couple and family therapy; innovative postgraduate training programs on site, in community settings and internationally; and, cutting edge research initiatives that support the development of new treatment models and new training techniques.  The Ackerman Institute is dedicated to helping families mobilize their strengths, resources and resilience to address and overcome the challenges they face.”</p>\r\n<h4>Thematic Centers</h4>\r\n<p>“The Ackerman Institute houses five thematic centers that respond to the changing needs of families. The knowledge and insights gained from the research undertaken in the centers are incorporated into Ackerman’s training programs and disseminated to mental health care professionals locally, nationally and internationally through lectures, workshops and publications.”&lt;</p>\r\n<p>Below are descriptions of three of the five centers.</p>\r\n<p>“The Center for the Developing Child and Family focuses on strengthening parent-child and family-school relationships in families with infants, toddlers, pre-school and elementary school children to support developmental competencies, school readiness and school success.</p>\r\n<p>The Center for Families and Health provides clinical services to couples and families who are experiencing acute, chronic or life-threatening illnesses, or coping with the death of a loved one. In addition, the Center offers training to medical professionals, family therapists and allied health care professionals, as well as consultations with health care facilities and staff.</p>\r\n<p>The Center for Work and Family maintains a number of community-based programs that assist families living in homeless shelters, families surviving domestic abuse, and recent immigrant families. The Center also serves families with significant wealth who are interested in developing effective tools to help their children maintain solid values and a sense of responsibility in a world of privilege.”</p>', 1, 11, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1365098734, 30, 1372444576, 0, 0, 0, 1365098640, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, 'research-categories/family/ackerman.html', 0, 0, 1, NULL),
(54, 'document', 'text/html', 'A Corporate Retreat for Teambuilding', 'A corporate retreat for teambuilding', '', 'a-corporate-retreat-for-teambuilding,', '', 1, 0, 0, 5, 0, '', '<p>Vineyards in Germany, Chile, Italy and California are capitalizing on their remote locations and engaging activities to attract corporate retreats. “The objective for large companies is to take their executives prisoner in order to concentrate their attention.” Add the fact that clients can participate in grape-crushing, wine blending and even bottle design and you have what many corporate clients are looking for, a “unique, customized event.”</p>', 1, 10, 3, 1, 1, 1, 1368122547, 1, 1386190395, 0, 0, 0, 1368101040, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, 'research-categories/articles/a-corporate-retreat-for-teambuilding,.html', 0, 0, 1, NULL),
(15, 'document', 'text/html', 'CIIS', '', '', 'ciis', '', 1, 0, 0, 3, 0, 'The CIIS is the largest single campus MFT (Marriage and Family Therapy) training program in California ', '<h2>Mission</h2>\r\n<p>"California Institute of Integral Studies is an accredited institution of higher education that strives to embody spirit, intellect, and wisdom in service to individuals, communities, and the Earth. The Institute expands the boundaries of traditional degree programs with interdisciplinary, cross-cultural, and applied studies in psychology, philosophy, religion, cultural anthropology, transformative learning and leadership, integrative health, and the arts. Offering a personal learning environment and supportive community, CIIS provides an extraordinary education for people committed to transforming themselves and the world"</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h2>History</h2>\r\n<p>CIIS was originally founded as the American Academy of Asian Studies attracting many leading figures of the “San Francisco Renaissance” and came to represent “the cutting-edge of Western absorption of the culture and spiritual practices of the East”. In 1973, the AAAS began adding offering programs in Integral Counseling Psychology, marking the start of its transformation from an Asian studies graduate school to a more diverse program offering and change its name from "Asian" to "Integral" in 1980, just as it received funding from Laurence Rockefeller; a library stands in his name.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h2>Programming</h2>\r\n<p><a title="Departments" href="http://www.ciis.edu/Academics/Departments.html" target="_blank">Departments</a>: ()</p>\r\n<p>The California Institute of Integral Studies is organized into three schools (Under Graduate, Graduate, Doctoral) which are themselves organized into departments:</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Interdisciplinary Studies </strong></p>\r\n<p>“With 15 to 22 fellow learners, you''ll study both multiple disciplines and various ways of knowing, such as kinesthetic, spiritual and intuitive. Students develop the capacity to improvise approaches to problems or issues, work collaboratively toward solutions, negotiate diverse viewpoints and become more adept technologically-skills valued in many professions, and that help you adapt as your career and workplace evolve.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Clinical Psychology </strong></p>\r\n<p>“The program’s training philosophy is based on the practitioner-scholar model of training that prepares students for professional practice in varying public and private contexts as active consumers of psychological science. The program endorses a broad understanding of psychological science which includes quantitative empirical science and methods as well as qualitative and experiential methods of inquiry.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Counseling Psychology </strong></p>\r\n<p>This program is divided into five concentrations:</p>\r\n<p>Community Mental Health</p>\r\n<p>Drama Therapy</p>\r\n<p>Expressive Arts Therapy</p>\r\n<p>Integral Counseling Psychology</p>\r\n<p>Somatic Psychology</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Philosophy and Religion </strong></p>\r\n<p>“The department administers the MA and PhD programs in Asian and Comparative Studies, Philosophy, Cosmology, and Consciousness, and Women''s Spirituality.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>East-West Psychology </strong></p>\r\n<p>“Founded in 1975, East-West Psychology (EWP) is a multidisciplinary department concerned with the meeting of Eastern, Western, and indigenous psychological and spiritual traditions.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Integrative Health Studies </strong></p>\r\n<p>“Integrative Health Studies is a two-year, nonclinical master''s degree program (40 units) that prepares graduates with a strategically designed career focus to enter the innovative field of integrative health and medicine. The curriculum blends knowledge and skill attainment in complementary, alternative and integrative medicine studies, professional skills in coaching and leadership, and practical knowledge in holistic therapies and self-care. ”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p><strong>Transformative Inquiry </strong></p>\r\n<p>“The Transformative Leadership MA is a uniquely innovative distance-learning program that integrates extensive practical skills with deep self-reflection and an emphasis on creative action in the world. The program prepares students to embody leadership and mobilize their creativity in many different ways, whether in organizations, social movements, or a range of activities requiring personal initiative and dedication to making a difference.”</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h2>Tuition/Price Points</h2>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="103">\r\n<p><strong>Program</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p><strong>Price/Unit</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p><strong>Course</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="103">\r\n<p>Undergraduate</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p>$640</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p>$25K</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="103">\r\n<p>Masters</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p>$943</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p>$33K-$56K</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top" width="103">\r\n<p>Doctoral</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p>$1089</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign="top" width="108">\r\n<p>$40K-$98K</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<h2>Contact</h2>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Director of Development</p>\r\n<p>Dorotea Reyna</p>\r\n<p>(415) 575-6135</p>\r\n<p><a href="mailto:dreyna@ciis.edu">dreyna@ciis.edu</a></p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Director of Communications</p>\r\n<p>Jim Martin</p>\r\n<p>(415) 575-6165</p>\r\n<p><a href="mailto:jmartin@ciis.edu">jmartin@ciis.edu</a></p>\r\n<h2> </h2>\r\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\r\n<p>The CIIS seems to be a well-managed institution with operating expenses of 14%, under the 15% non-profit benchmark. However, the American Psychological Association revoked their accreditation of the Doctoral program in Clinical Psychology in 2011, citing that “The program was deemed to be not fully consistent with the <em>Guidelines and Principles for Accreditation of Programs in Professional Psychology</em> (G&amp;P).” They have responded saying: “our students continue to get licensed and have higher pass rates on the national psychology exam over the last five years than any APA approved Psy.D. program in our area, and we will continue to provide innovative and cutting edge training to our future clinical psychologists”.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>The CIIS has also recently expanded to a larger 80,000 square foot facility in the South-of-Market district of San Francisco, an up and coming hub for innovative tech companies, some of which are high-profile contributors to the CIIS. </p>', 1, 11, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1365453004, 30, 1372444410, 0, 0, 0, 1365098640, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, 'research-categories/learning/ciis.html', 0, 0, 1, NULL),
