(96, 'document', 'text/html', 'Retail-Restaurant, Restaurant-Retail', 'Eataly, Il Laboatorio del Gelato, Miss Lil''s ', '', 'community-builders', '', 1, 0, 0, 93, 0, 'Restaurants with strong retail components are able to capture otherwise untapped revenues as well as reenforce their brand. The strongest players in this category achieve an almost seamless unity of product and plate and invite guests to more fully embrace their culinary philosophies. Miss Lily''s and Eataly have almost equal parts market and restaurant, while Il Laboritorio''s store front is just the tip of the gelato iceburg.', '<h3>Eataly</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/20120703_birdsEye_eataly.png" title="Eataly Market" alt="Eataly Market" />\r\n\r\n <p>\r\n 	Eataly is a market f&amp;b concept on a grand scale. Mario Betali, Joe Bastianich, and Lidia Bastianich have created a fantasy land of Italian food, produce, and education. <i>"we cook what we sell, and we sell what we cook"</i> is the philosophy and it applies to everything from the meat to the bread to the cookbooks and equipment. The trio''s decades of experience are embedded in the layout, showing a keen awareness of diner''s interests, shopper''s habits and retail best practices. The meanering halls seem random, but a closer look reveals a clearly organized path that presents the guest with various moments to explore. The apparent absence of checkout points (until of course you reach them at just the right time) engenders the feeling that you are truly in a market, populated by individual salesmen all cooperating in an invisible hand kind of way to deliver a holistic culinary/retail experience. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Eataly_Restaurant.png" title="Eataly Restaurant" alt="Eataly Restaurant" />\r\n\r\n<p>	\r\n	The Eataly trio are, in a sense, making a fortune by giving away their secrets: they invite people into the kitchen with cooking classes, they sell both the recipes and raw materials from which their dishes are made with the market and library, and offer expertise to shoppers at the various sales points. Their true success however is about their larger than life personalities, sophisticated sensibilities, and decades of experience; things that cannot be replicated.   \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n\r\n<h3>Miss Lily''s</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Miss-Lily''s_Interior.png" title="Miss Lily''s Juicer" alt="Miss Lily''s Juicer" />\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Miss Lily''s started life as a Jamaican style restaurant, founded by ''scene-maker'' and nightclub owner, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/28/fashion/serge-becker-night-life-impresario.html?pagewanted=all" target="_blank">Serge Becker</a>. Miss Lily''s is widley hailed as the premier Carribean cuisine in the city, thanks to chef Bradford Thompson. Thompson, a James Beard award for Best Chef apprentice of Daniel Boulud marries his classical training with his family''s Jamaican traditional spices, resulting in technicaly excellent and highly flavorful food.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Miss-Lily''s_Juicer.png" title="Miss Lily''s Juicer" alt="Miss Lily''s Juicer" />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	In 2011 <a href="http://nymag.com/restaurants/features/15920/" target="_blank">Major Melvin</a>, long-time celbrity juice maker (he made juices for Gwenyth Paltrow and others for 16 years) joined Miss Lily''s to open up Melvin''s Juice Box in an adjacent space. The juice bar has become wildly popular and has gained a gold star reputation, even amid the oversaturation of the fresh juice market and was awarded <a href="http://nymag.com/bestofny/food/2012/juice-bar/" target="_blank">"best juice bar of 2012"</a> by the New York Times. This year Melvin launched his juice clense program: a pre-ordered 1, 3 or 5-day clense charged at $60 a day. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131205_Miss-Lily''s_Radio_620.png" title="Miss Lily''s Radio" alt="Miss Lily''s Radio" />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Miss Lily''s also consists of a variety store selling vinyl records, CDs and apparel as well as an internet radio station featuring notable DJs.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Miss Lily''s has managed it''s growth well, building a strong foundation with the dinner menu in the restaurant, expanding to lunch and highly profitable juices, installing a radio station and starting to bottle and sell their sauces, juices, and spices. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class="further_reading">\r\n	<h3>Further Reading:</h3>\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>\r\n				<a href="http://newyork.seriouseats.com/2011/08/miss-lilys-serious-jamaican-food-from-a-serio.html" target="_blank">Serious Eats</a> \r\n			</li>\r\n			<li>\r\n				<a href="http://www.grubstreet.com/2011/08/house-style-miss-lilys.html" tagret="_blank">Grub Street</a>\r\n			</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n</div><!-- further_reading -->\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n\r\n<h3>Il Laboratorio del Gelato</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Il-Laboratorio-del-Gelato_Counter.png" title="Il Laboritorio Counter" alt="Il Laboritorio Counter" />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Jon Snyder began working in his family owned Carvel Ice Cream franchise at an early age, but always had a taste for the experimental. His exploration lead to two enterprises: Ciao Bella which he later sold to attend Columbia business school and his current project, Il Laboratorio del Gelato. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Il-Laboratorio-del-Gelato_Machines.png" title="Il Laboritorio Machines" alt="Il Laboritorio Machines" />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	At Il Laboratorio fresh ingredients are prepared by hand and crafted into unusual flavors; avocado, black peppercorn, rosemary, olive oil, and Guinness to name a few. Jon works closely with local restaurants to create custom gelatos for their menus and has produced over 200 new flavors with his chef collaborators. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<i>\r\n	“Chefs can come, consult and experiment to create innovative flavors for their restaurants.”\r\n</i>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Although the Lab’s two machines churn out gelato non-stop for 10 hours a day, Jon has turned down many requests for expansion, saying “With food bigger is not better, smaller is better”. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<i>\r\n	“We want to be the best gelato address in New York City and that means we have to stay small and exclusive. And we aim to continue working hand in glove with the foremost chefs. That is and will remain our core business”.\r\n</i> \r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	90% of Il Laboratorio’s business comes from wholesale customers. Only a small portion of The Lab’s gelato is sold retail but by opening up to the public Jon has kept the critics interested and Il Laboratorio’s name in the press.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Il Laboratorio has not just been a success for its founder but also for the then up and coming neighborhood it occupies. <i>“We were really the first to be there. There was nothing south of Delancey Street then but fabric shops.”</i> \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Its stores like Jon’s that draw a crowd seeking artisanal products and unique experiences that are helping to transform Manhattan’s Lower Eastside from a predominantly lower-class working neighborhood into one of the trendiest locations in the city. Since Il Laboratorio moved to the area in 2002, median rent prices have increased from $738 to $1375 beating the New York City average increase by 28%.\r\n</p>', 0, 14, 2, 1, 1, 1, 1386351334, 1, 1386616921, 0, 0, 0, 1386353220, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, '', 0, 0, 1, NULL),
(97, 'document', 'text/html', 'Conceptual Dining', 'Momofuku, Rouge Tomate, M Wells', '', 'retail-restaurant,-restaurant-retail', '', 1, 0, 0, 93, 0, 'Some restauranteurs seek to challenge diners. They make the familiar strange and the strange familiar or introduce brand new concepts. This is perhaps the riskiest of apraoches, but as M Wells and Momofuku show, the rewards can be enormous.', '<h3>Momofuku</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Momofuku_Labeld-Dinner.png" title="Momofuku Dinner" alt="Momofuku Dinner" />	\r\n\r\n<p> 	\r\n	Momofuku Ssam Bar is highly accessible. It draws crowds looking for a quick cheap pork bun + cocktail or larger groups for the Bo Ssam feast, all of which can be got for about $25/person, drinks and other dishes excluded. Yet, despite the casual atmosphere, <a href="http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/david-chang-the-anxiety-of-influence/#1" target="_blank">Davig Chang</a> (one of the more famed New York restaurant royals) makes no bones about experimentation.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="quote">\r\n	Mr. Chang trusts diners not to be disoriented by an assortment of dishes without any instantly clear theme or overriding ethnic allegiance — by platters of artisanal American hams next to a tangle of Sichuan-style beef tendon alongside a hanger steak with a romesco sauce. He pulls off this eclecticism, which could easily lapse into incoherence, by keeping the menu sufficiently succinct and making sure everything on it counts.\r\n</p>  \r\n\r\n  <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/restaurants/1154665997851/momofuku-ssam-bar/details.html" target="_blank">New York Times</a>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Chang manages a portfolio of restaurants that are the perfect high-low mix. He brought downtown to uptown with Ma Peche, and uptown dining downtown with Momofuku Ko, a twelve seater bar that has been likened more to a private dining club than a restaurant. His ubiquitous Milk Bar serves ice-cream sandwiches and coffee, with Momofuku Ssam Bar occupying the middle ground.\r\n </p>\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n\r\n<h3>Rouge Tomate and S.P.E.</h3>  \r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_Rouge-Tomate_Plate.png" title="Rouge Tomate Plate" alt="Rouge Tomate PLate" />\r\n \r\n<p>\r\n	Rouge Tomate is trying to kick-start SPE (Sanitas Per Escam, Latin for “health through food”) by acting as an ambassador for the fledgling third-party certification program. The program is designed to be "the universal, trusted standard for healthy and delicious dining outside the home."  \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	SPE was founded by Emmanuel Verstraeten, founder of Rouge Tomate in Brussels and Manhattan, and adheres to specific guidelines developed by a team of nutritionists. The curly red logo is supposed to signify that the food conforms to three main standards:\r\n</p>\r\n<br class="clear"/>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>It is balanced (excludes bad fats, butters and generally contains more of what you need, and less of what you don''t)</li>\r\n	<li>It is environmentally sensitive (for example the animal is not on the endangered list)</li>\r\n	<li>It is tasty</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Emmanuel Verstraeten''s vision is to have all manner of establishments sign on, from restaurants to college cafeterias to fast food establishments. They have had some success gaining large institutional support having signed on UC Davis and UMass Amherst to the program.  \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	The SPE standards are proprietary and so when a restaurant signs on, they will have an SPE team evaluate their menu for nutritional value according to their standards. The SPE team will then work with the chef to implement certain changes to the menu item and evaluate proposed additions. The restaurant may then display the SPE logo next to the menu item. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>SPE certification level:</p>\r\n<br class="clear"/>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Certified (3/10%)</li>\r\n	<li>Silver (25%) </li>\r\n	<li>Gold (50%)</li>\r\n	<li>Platinum (75%)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Which level an establishment achieves, is based on the percentage of SPE certified dishes available on the menu.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	Once certified, the restaurant will appear on the SPE website, along wit a nutritional breakdown of the certified meals they offer.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://specertified.com/restaurants/arabelle-at-hotel-plaza-athenee/arabelle-arctic-char" title="SPE certification" target="_blank">See a sample here.</a></p>\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n\r\n<h3>M. Wells</h3>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_MoMA-PS1_Class-in-Session.png" title="M Wells Dining Room" alt="M Wells Dining Room" />\r\n\r\n<p>M Wells is housed in [MOMA PS1](http://www.momaps1.com). The dining room is set up cafeteria style, keeping with the aesthetic of the building, which was a functioning school until 1963. Menus are written on chalk boards and diners are sat at school desks, seated in school chairs, facing the kitchen. The setup suggests that you are there to recieve an education from the chef, and the changing menu written on a chalk board, serves to reinforce the theme.</p> \r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_M-Wells_Chalkboard.png" title="M Wells Chalkboard" alt="M Wells Chalkboard" />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	The dishes are bold and whimsical and almost always unexpected, revolving generally around the theme of nose-to-tail dining. M Wells is unabashedly decadent, serving rich comfort food (rabbit and foie gras terrine, foie gras oatmeal, veal brain and sweet-breads). \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<img src="assets/research assets/hospitality/images/131105_M-Wells_Burger.png" title="M Wells Burger" alt="M Wells Burger" />\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	M Wells treats cuisine as high art, and is perfectly matched to it''s museum host. Plates are best enjoyed shared, creating a communal learning experience.\r\n</p>  \r\n\r\n<p>\r\n	M Wells expands this year with a full service steakhouse.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="further_reading">\r\n	<h3>Further Reading:</h3>\r\n		<ul>\r\n			<li>\r\n				<a href="http://www.newyorker.com/arts/reviews/tables/2013/05/20/130520gota_GOAT_tables_goldfield" target="_blank">New Yorker Review</a> \r\n			</li>\r\n			<li>\r\n				<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/21/dining/reviews/restaurant-review-m-wells-dinette-at-moma-ps1.html?pagewanted=2" target="_blank">New York Times</a>\r\n			</li>\r\n			<li>\r\n				<a href="http://newyork.seriouseats.com/2012/10/m-wells-dinette-dufour-obraitis-ps1-moma-cafe-long-island-city-opening-review.html" target="_blank">Serious Eats</a>\r\n			</li>\r\n		</ul>\r\n</div><!-- further_reading -->', 0, 14, 3, 1, 1, 1, 1386352904, 1, 1386616904, 0, 0, 0, 1386353220, 1, '', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'modDocument', 'web', 1, '', 0, 0, 1, NULL);
